  Day3MetBeforeDialog: []
  Day4FirstTimeDialog: []
  Day4MetBeforeDialog: []
  Day5FirstTimeDialog: []
  Day5MetBeforeDialog: []
  Day6Dialog:
  - 'They placed me near the batteries, close enough that every shot runs through
    my bones.

    The guns work without pause, and the men believe the fort cannot
    endure this for long.

    My task is to keep pace with certainty: straighten,
    bind, return.

    There is confidence in this camp, heavy and unquestioned.

    By
    tomorrow, I suspect I will learn how much damage certainty can ignore.'
  Day7FirstTimeDialog:
  - 'Armour comes back distorted, not cut.

    Helmets crushed inward by force no
    blade could deliver, shields split without a mark of steel.

    The men joke
    as they drop the pieces at my feet, already certain they will not need them much
    longer.

    I work faster than I should.

    By tomorrow, I fear speed will
    replace judgement entirely.'
  Day7MetBeforeDialog:
  - 'Yesterday, I took care with every repair.

    Today, the same man returned,
    his armour bent so badly I had to tear it free.

    He asked if the fort would
    fall soon.

    I told him yes, because everyone says yes.

    By tomorrow,
    I will understand how easily belief passes from mouth to mouth without touching
    truth.'
  Day8FirstTimeDialog:
  - "The bombardment has changed the way damage looks.\nMen arrive shaken rather
    than wounded, their gear fractured in places they haven\u2019t noticed yet.\nWe
    reuse straps, rivets, scraps taken from those who no longer need them.\nNo one
    asks how long the repairs will last.\nBy tomorrow, I fear I will stop asking
    myself the same question."
  Day8MetBeforeDialog:
  - 'Today, I repaired armour knowing exactly where it would fail.

    I could have
    reinforced it, but time mattered more than strength.

    The man thanked me
    and returned to the line without hesitation.

    I watched him go, aware that
    my choice would meet him again.

    By tomorrow, I will carry that awareness
    without reacting to it.'
  Day9FirstTimeDialog:
  - 'The work has become rhythm.

    Strike, listen, bind, pass it on.

    If the
    metal answers, it returns to the assault.

    If it does not, it is stripped
    and reused.

    By tomorrow, I suspect I will measure worth only by whether
    something still moves forward.'
  Day9MetBeforeDialog:
  - 'A Janissary asked me how long his armour would hold.

    I told him what I
    thought he needed to hear, not what I knew.

    He adjusted the straps himself,
    tighter than necessary, as if pressure alone could make it true.

    By tomorrow,
    I fear I will no longer recognise the moment when honesty mattered.'
  Day10FirstTimeDialog:
  - 'Today, the guns faltered.

    Not because the fort resisted, but because word
    passed through the camp faster than orders: Dragut is dead.

    Men brought
    armour that did not need repair and asked me to check it anyway.

    I did,
    because touching metal was easier than touching the truth.

    By tomorrow,
    I fear I will understand that victory was never as certain as we pretended.'
  Day10MetBeforeDialog:
  - "Dragut died today.\nThey did not announce it; they let it spread, as if speaking
    it too loudly might break something else.\nA man stood before me holding his
    armour, waiting for me to tell him it would be enough.\nI worked in silence,
    knowing I could no longer promise that.\nBy tomorrow, if the assault continues,
    I will be shaping metal for men who now know that even certainty can be killed
    \u2014 and that knowledge will weigh more than any armour I can give them."
